----------------------------------------------------------------
1. ABOUT THE PROGRAM
----------------------------------------------------------------

Anteater Chess is a variant of classical chess played on an
8 x 10 board that introduces a new piece: the anteater. The
anteater moves one square in any direction (like a king) but
cannot threaten the enemy king. Instead, it feeds on ants
(pawns) and can capture a row of adjacent ants in a single move.

This program allows a human user to play interactive Anteater
Chess against a computer opponent through a graphical user
interface (GTK). The user chooses their side (white or black),
and the computer plays the opposing side. All moves are
recorded to a human-readable log file.


----------------------------------------------------------------
2. FEATURES (ALPHA)
----------------------------------------------------------------

Required features:
  * Full Anteater Chess rule set (including anteater and ants)
  * Graphical user interface (GTK-based board and pieces)
  * Human vs. computer gameplay
  * Player color selection (white or black)
  * Human-readable move log (chess_game.log)
  * Computer moves completed in reasonable time

Bonus features implemented:
  * Undo function (withdraw previous moves)

Known limitations (alpha):
  * Some illegal move checks may be incomplete
  * AI plays at a single difficulty level
  * Occasional instability in special-move handling


----------------------------------------------------------------
3. BUILD AND RUN
----------------------------------------------------------------

See the INSTALL file for detailed installation steps.

Quick start:
    $ make
    $ ./bin/chess

For gameplay instructions, rules, and controls, see:
    doc/Chess_UserManual.pdf

For software architecture details, see:
    doc/Chess_SoftwareSpec.pdf


----------------------------------------------------------------
4. SOURCE FILE OVERVIEW
----------------------------------------------------------------

The source code is organized into modules. Each module consists
of a header file (.h) that declares the public API and a source
file (.c) that provides the implementation.

--- Core entry point ---

main.c
    Program entry point. Prompts the user to choose a color,
    initializes the board, and runs the main game loop. Each
    iteration displays the board, accepts a move from the
    current player (human input or AI call), executes the move,
    checks for checkmate/stalemate, and switches turns.

--- Data types and constants ---

enum.h
    Shared enumerations and constants used across every module:
      - Rank (KING, QUEEN, ANTEATER, BISHOP, KNIGHT, ROOK, ANT)
      - Color (BLACK, WHITE)
      - Piece_Type (color + rank combined)
      - Board dimensions: BOARD_HEIGHT = 8, BOARD_WIDTH = 10
      - Window/square pixel sizes for the GUI
    Acts as the single source of truth for cross-module types.

pieces.h / pieces.c
    Defines the Piece struct (image, color, rank, value, and a
    vtable of function pointers) and the Pos struct (row, col).
    Provides per-piece movement and capture logic:
      - rookCanMove, bishopCanMove, knightCanMove, queenCanMove,
        kingCanMove, pawnCanMove, anteaterCanMove
      - pawnCanCapture, anteaterCanCapture
    Each function takes the board plus start/end coordinates
    and returns whether that piece can legally make that move.
    This is the "chess rules" module.

board.h / board.c
    Defines the Board struct (2D array of Piece pointers) and
    a Board_State struct that tracks the currently clicked
    piece and update flags (used for GUI interaction).
    Provides:
      - Board setup: createPieces, createAnts,
        initializeBoard, defaultInitializeBoard
      - Lookup/mutation: getSquare, setSquare, hasPiece,
        addPiece, deletePiece, movePiece
      - Board state: aPieceWasClicked, newPieceWasClicked,
        sendInput (handles click-to-move logic)
    This is the central data structure for the whole program.

move.h / move.c
    Defines the Move struct (start row/col, end row/col, capture
    flag) and execution functions:
      - executeMove       (basic move)
      - executeCapture    (generic capture)
      - executePawnCapture (sideways pawn capture)
      - executeAnteaterCapture (chain-capture of ants)
      - recordMove       (append to the move log)
    Called by main after a move has been validated by pieces.c.

--- User input ---

input.h / input.c
    Parses and classifies user input from the textual command
    line (used in debug mode and before the GUI is active):
      - inputHasMove, inputIsCastleKingSide,
        inputIsCastleQueenSide, inputIsUndo, inputIsQuit
      - inputGetStartPos, inputGetEndPos
    Also provides isValid for input sanity-checking. Designed
    so main can dispatch on the type of input without knowing
    the string format.

--- Computer opponent ---

ai.h / ai.c
    Implements the computer player. The public entry point is
    aiSelectMove(player, out), which fills in a Move struct
    with the AI's chosen move. Internally scans all pieces of
    the given color, generates legal candidate moves using the
    rules from pieces.c, and picks a move based on a simple
    evaluation heuristic (piece values, captures).

--- Move history and undo ---

log.h / log.c
    Maintains a human-readable text log of the game. Functions:
      - newLog        (start a fresh log file)
      - addMove       (append a standard move)
      - addCapture    (append a capture)
      - addCastle     (append a castling move)
    The log file is named chess_game.log and is written after
    every executed move, satisfying the "human readable log"
    requirement from the project spec.

undo.h / undo.c
    Implements the undo feature (bonus requirement). Maintains
    an internal stack of executed moves:
      - undoSet    (initialize the stack)
      - undoPush   (record a move after it executes)
      - undoPop    (remove the most recent move)
      - undo       (restore the board to the previous state)
    Called from main when the user issues an undo command.

--- Graphical user interface (gui/) ---

gui/gui.h / gui/gui.c
    GTK application entry point. Creates the main window,
    installs the CSS styling, builds the board widget, and
    wires up click events:
      - createWindow, createBoard, setBackground
      - onClick       (translates a pixel click into a board
                       position via whichSquare / pixToIndex)
      - activate      (GTK application activation callback)
    Bridges user clicks to board/board-state updates.

gui/render.h / gui/render.c
    Responsible for drawing the board and pieces on screen
    using Cairo. Provides:
      - drawSquare, drawPiece, drawBoard
      - scale         (scales a piece image to the target size)
      - createImages  (loads piece textures from resources/)
      - pixToIndex / indexToPix (pixel <-> board-index math)
    Defines Board_Bundle, which ties together the Board, the
    Board_State, and the GtkWidget so callbacks can access all
    three at once.

gui/color_gui.h / gui/color_gui.c
    Color scheme and CSS helpers for the GUI:
      - BLACK_SQUARE, WHITE_SQUARE (board square colors)
      - colorCtor, RGBtoGTK (RGBA construction helpers)
      - CHESS_BG    (CSS class name for the window background)

gui/resources/
    PNG images for each of the 14 piece types (white/black x
    king/queen/anteater/bishop/knight/rook/pawn) loaded at
    startup by render.c.


----------------------------------------------------------------
5. MODULE INTERACTION
----------------------------------------------------------------

  user input ----> input.c --+
                             |
                             v
  gui/ (clicks) ----> main.c ----> pieces.c (rule check)
                             |         |
                             |         v
                             +----> move.c (execute)
                             |         |
                             |         +----> board.c (mutate)
                             |         |
                             |         +----> log.c (record)
                             |         |
                             |         +----> undo.c (push)
                             |
                             +----> ai.c (computer's move)
                             |         ^
                             |         +----> pieces.c
                             |
                             +----> gui/render.c (redraw)


----------------------------------------------------------------
6. DIRECTORY LAYOUT
----------------------------------------------------------------

    chess/
    |-- README                     This file
    |-- COPYRIGHT                  Copyright notice
    |-- INSTALL                    Installation instructions
    |-- Makefile                   Build rules (make/test/clean/tar)
    |-- main.c                     Program entry point
    |-- enum.h                     Shared enums and constants
    |-- pieces.{c,h}               Piece data and rule checks
    |-- board.{c,h}                Board data and operations
    |-- move.{c,h}                 Move struct and execution
    |-- input.{c,h}                User input parsing
    |-- ai.{c,h}                   Computer opponent
    |-- log.{c,h}                  Move logging
    |-- undo.{c,h}                 Undo functionality
    |-- gui/
    |   |-- gui.{c,h}              GTK app and window
    |   |-- render.{c,h}           Cairo drawing
    |   |-- color_gui.{c,h}        Color scheme
    |   `-- resources/             Piece images
    |-- bin/                       Built executable (after make)
    `-- doc/
        |-- Chess_UserManual.pdf   Application specification
        `-- Chess_SoftwareSpec.pdf Software architecture spec


